function decode_permutation(s) {
    const n = s.length;
    const perm = new Array(n + 1);
    let next_zero = 0, next_one = n;

    for (const c of s) {
        if (c === '0') {
            perm[next_zero++] = next_one--;
        } else {
            perm[next_one--] = next_zero++;
        }
    }
    perm[next_zero] = next_one;
    return perm;
}
```


    The algorithm initializes the result array `perm` and two pointers `next_zero` and `next_one`. The `next_zero` pointer starts at 0, and the `next_one` pointer starts at the last position of `perm`.

Then, the algorithm iterates through the given string `s`:
- If the current character is '0', the algorithm assigns the value of `next_one` to the position pointed by `next_zero`, then increments `next_zero`, and decrements `next_one`.
- If the current character is '1', the algorithm assigns the value of `next_zero` to the position pointed by `next_one`, then increments `next_zero`, and decrements `next_one`.

After iterating through the whole string `s`, the remaining unused value will be in `next_one`. We assign this value to the position pointed by `next_zero` in the `perm` array.

At the end of the algorithm, the constructed `perm` array represents a valid permutation.

